Base classes are different from constructor/initializer arguments. Both classes should simply inherit from `object` (though in Python 3 you don&#39;t need to do so explicitly. The place for one or more arguments is in the definition of `__init__` (or `__new__`, but we&#39;ll keep this simple):

    class Class1:
        def __init__(self, str1):
            ...

    class Class2:
        def __init__(self, str1, str2):
            ...

If you do specify additional base classes, they must be *unique*.

    # Illegal
    class Class1(object, object):
        ...

    # Legal, even though str also inherits from obj
    # Don&#39;t actually do this, though.
    class Class1(str, object):
       ...
 
    # Legal: preferred version of the above
    class Class1(str):
